<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Static Dungeons are on its way, and we will be using a system where we can control the amount of people allowed to enter one dungeon before its considered full. What happens when a set amount of players is inside a dungeon, is that a new copy of that dungeon is “spawned”. This in itself makes a dungeon more playable, but on the other hand you may not end up in the same dungeon as your friends. If any in your team is already inside, you will be able to enter the same dungeon no matter the limit.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To make sure we have all the information to argue about this, this is an idea that came up a lot in EQ.  For those of you not versed in the issue, let’s assume you have a 5-room dungeon.  Each room has a special mob that can spawn there, and a few regular spawns.  What would happen is a group would set up “camp” on 1 or more rooms, and then just sit there “camping” the NPC’s for experience and for gear from the special mob … most of EQ’s dungeon-zones, in fact, are set up on this principle.<br>
<br>
The problem is that say you and your friends want to camp Philip Ross to get his +10 Executive Washroom Towel of Doom one night.  You get all grouped up, tromp over to the dungeon and unfortunately, another group’s already camping it.  Granted you could go kill-steal for it, but in general you just have to move along.  Given a limited number of good spots to level at in a static dungeon for your level, this quickly leads to a lot of issues with crowding being at the top.  I remember as a monk in EQ being able, after a while, to walk from the entrance to Lower Guk to the King’s room and never see a mob because every single camp-spot was taken.  Not only does this suck, but it causes player conflicts, gets customer-service involved in camping disputes, raises the issue of “farming” (basically, camping something for multiple copies of a piece of gear to sell, either in-game or on like eBay).  It’s a mess.<br>
<br>
What Funcom is proposing is a possible solution wherein a dungeon would have a maximum number of players in the zone, and if that max were reached the next people in would enter a clone of it.  Verant refused to do this for a variety of reasons, including that it just didn’t seem “realistic” (that always cracked me up), but foremost I would imagine are the coding difficulties involved and the possible exploits of the system it can create.<br>
<br>
So at lunch today I’m pondering this, and I decided to put on a game designer’s hat and think about how I’d solve the issue.  My solution may be naïve, perhaps, but it is workable I think and solves one or two of the problems I’ve encountered personally and/or I could foresee in this multiple/static environment being suggested.<br>
<br>
what I was thinking was why not just use the group mission terminals?  So let’s say there are 5 static dungeons in Pleasant Meadows.  To get in, you go to the group mission terminal in Pleasant Meadows and after the usual 6 random missions, there are 5 extra missions, one for each of those dungeons, with the same goal – kill the “boss mob” at the end of the dungeon.  When you go to the location, it spawns you the same dungeon it always does but your group’s the only one inside of it – if you want multiple teams, you simply dupe the key for whoever you want inside.  Then your group or your entire guild or whoever can enjoy a static zone all to yourself.<br>
<br>
How do you deal with the uber-loot issues?  In EQ, dragons and Gods would spawn roughly once a week.  What would happen is the uberest guild would get there and whack it.  It got so ridiculous that there were, and probably still are, schedules for which guild was “allowed” to do it that week, and everyone was supposed to take turns … i.e., take a number and wait in line.  Not only was it frustrating and laughable, it wasn’t fun.  The only way I can see implementing uber mobs / loot is by making their appearance timed, and random, so you don’t know if it’s loaded until you are in the actual dungeon, have fought all the way down, and see it.  Whether it spawns or not would be decided when the key is generated, so you could not just leave someone down there to wait for it to spawn.  Then if you need help, you get on the ‘com and get the guild to rally the troops.  It’s not a perfect solution, but it is workable.<br>
<br>
What is your solution?  Or do you dislike the whole cloned-static-dungeon concept altogether?  Discuss.<br>
