<br>
It's a good idea but all it does is change the nature of farming. To wit:<br>
<br>
Team missions give key to dungeon. Easy enough. Have, say, five teams. Each team pulls one of those missions each in the same place, pulling over and over until you get that exact spot. Dupe the other four. Slaughter your way through with 5x the number it's designed for. (If there are population limitations, players will quickly learn how many people are max and have that many.) Also to note is that teams have to hit the same occurrence of the mission; otherwise, why have keys.<br>
<br>
If you scale mobs for the 5x overkill expectation, people do 10 teams with half the numbers. Or 20 teams with 1/4 the numbers, so they'll have a ton of keys. Because a single team alone won't be able to do it without the overkill. And how do you know if they're overkilling or not?<br>
<br>
Yes, you won't have competing teams any more, which is good. You'll only have a flood of &quot;uniques&quot;, which can be bad, depending on the nature of the unique/rare. And if you don't make it rare or unique--and valuable besides--you run into the same problem as mission terms have now. &quot;Wtf, they want me to go to Perpetual for a red cloak hood?!&quot;<br>
<br>
It seems to me there is no way to balance the risk/reward of a static mission against camping against exploitation/farming. Not unless the mission itself is dynamic and adjusts <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  after everyone with a key is inside</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and even then you've got the issues of farming and adequate reward for risk... one of which feeds into the other.<br>
<br>
You'll pardon me if I don't believe the 'Com has the coding savvy to pull anything remotely like that off. :)<br>
<br>
Oh, and edit: I've nothing against static dungeons, in either concept or execution. My favorite solution to camping (I didn't make it up, and I don't remember who did) is simply gradually increase the respawn of mobs in that area/region/zone/what-have-you as more people get there. At some point, it will become so overwhelming that you'll have to flee or die. And yes, this opens up the possibility of &quot;grief spawning&quot;--jacking up the spawn rate and then running, leaving the uber spawn rate for the next group to hit that area--but no solution is perfect. Besides, if this jacked rate were common knowledge, you'd be wary entering a new area anyway. Which, to my mind, is as it should be. :) <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bthepunchingbag74708.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=alianna>Alianna</A> at: 10/2/01 3:34:49 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#99CC66><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/ualloca.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Alloca</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Training Dummy</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#660000>(10/2/01 3:56:14 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Erm...</span><hr size=1> Are we discussing the right way to do it? Or how they will do it?<br>
